You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput Spring Boot gateway service occasionally throws a `ConcurrentModificationException` under heavy traffic. The service caches active user routes using a custom LRU map. A background thread periodically logs the cached keys, while incoming requests read routes from the cache. Here is the implementation:

java
@Component
public class RouteCache {
    private final Map<String, Route> cache = Collections.synchronizedMap(
        new LinkedHashMap<>(100, 0.75f, true) { // access-order = true
            @Override
            protected boolean removeEldestEntry(Map.Entry<String, Route> eldest) {
                return size() > 100;
            }
        }
    );

    public Route getRoute(String id) {
        return cache.get(id); 
    }

    @Scheduled(fixedRate = 60000)
    public void logCacheKeys() {
        for (String key : cache.keySet()) { 
            System.out.println("Active Route: " + key);
        }
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a low-latency trading application experiences catastrophic GC pauses. Profiling reveals that a custom high-performance ring buffer queue, designed to avoid GC overhead by recycling nodes, is actually causing high garbage collection pressure. The queue uses an array of custom node wrappers to store elements:

java
public class RecyclableQueue<T> {
    private final Node<T>[] buffer;
    private long tail = 0;
    private long head = 0;

    private static class Node<T> {
        T value;
    }

    public void offer(T item) {
        Node<T> node = buffer[(int)(tail++ % buffer.length)];
        node.value = item; // Mutating long-lived object's reference field
    }
}

After a few minutes of operation, the ring buffer itself (and its `Node` wrapper instances) migrates to the JVM Old Generation.

You are debugging a production issue where a multithreaded order processing engine occasionally drops orders under high concurrency. The engine uses a custom lock-free concurrent linked list implementation using `VarHandle` to manage append operations. Under stress testing, some orders are silently lost (they are never linked into the list, although the producer threads complete successfully).

java
public class ConcurrentAppendList<E> {
    private static class Node<E> {
        final E item;
        volatile Node<E> next;
        Node(E item) { this.item = item; }
    }

    private volatile Node<E> head;
    private volatile Node<E> tail;
    private static final VarHandle TAIL;
    // VarHandle is correctly initialized targeting the tail field

    public void append(E item) {
        Node<E> newNode = new Node<>(item);
        for (;;) {
            Node<E> t = tail;
            if (TAIL.compareAndSet(this, t, newNode)) {
                t.next = newNode; // Subtle flaw
                return;
            }
        }
    }
}
